      },
      "lineNbr": 188,
      "author": {
        "id": 1000411
      },
      "writtenOn": "2014-02-14T16:22:51Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This seems to be not directly related to x86_64 support (i.e. this affects x86 as well), and I wonder if this could actually introduce regressions for existing x86 system images. Can I ask you to put that in a separate patch instead. It\u0027s better to put logically distinct changes in separate patches, because fixing regressions often involves bisecting.",
      "revId": "d80391eba0f4c6a247957834e8bb6879801013c4",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "4fda4934_65af82a9",
        "filename": "hw/intc/ioapic.c",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 50,
      "author": {
        "id": 1000411
      },
      "writtenOn": "2014-02-14T16:22:51Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "At first, I though this broke snapshotting, but it turns out that this field is never saved to / restored from snapshots anyway (!) This is a bug, and looking at upstream, it seems they have fixed it.\n\nSo I guess we can accept that, but please add comment stating that this was increased to 64-bit intentionally (upstream still uses a uint32_t here, and I\u0027m going to back-port the new ioapic implementation at some point into our tree).\n\nBtw, do you know how upstream manages this with only 32-bit pins? I\u0027d be curious to know if we can use the same scheme asap.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 50,
        "startChar": 13,
        "endLine": 50,
        "endChar": 16
      },
      "revId": "d80391eba0f4c6a247957834e8bb6879801013c4",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
